===Etymology 1===
From {{etyl|enm|en}} {{term|beggen|lang=enm}}, assimilation from {{etyl|ang|en}} *{{term||bedican|lang=ang}}, syncopated variant of {{term|bedecian||to beg|lang=ang}}. Related to {{etyl|got|-}} {{term|𐌱𐌹𐌳𐌰𐌲𐍅𐌰||tr=bidagwa|beggar|lang=got}}, {{etyl|ang|-}} {{term|biddan||to ask|lang=ang}}. More at {{l/en|bid}}, {{l/en|bead}}.

====Verb====
{{en-verb|beg|g|ed}}

# {{context|intransitive|lang=en}} to request the help of someone, often in the form of money
#: ''He '''begged''' on the street corner from passers-by.''
# {{context|transitive|lang=en}} to [[plead]] with someone for help, a favor, etc.; to [[entreat]]
#: ''I '''beg''' your pardon. I didn't mean to cause offence.''
#: ''He '''begged''' her to go to the prom with him''.
#* Shakespeare
#*: I do '''beg''' your good will in this case.
#* Bible, Matthew xxvii. 58
#*: [Joseph] '''begged''' the body of Jesus.
#* '''1898''', {{w|J. Meade Falkner}}, {{w|Moonfleet}} Chapter 5
#*: But that same day came Sam Tewkesbury to the Why Not? about nightfall, and '''begged''' a glass of rum, being, as he said, 'all of a shake'{{...}}
# {{context|transitive|lang=en}} to assume, in the phrase {{term|beg the question}}
# {{context|proscribed|lang=en}} to [[raise]] a question, in the phrase {{term|beg the question}}
# {{cx|legal|obsolete|lang=en}} To ask to be appointed guardian for, or to ask to have a guardian appointed for.
#* Harrington
#*: Else some will '''beg''' thee, in the court of wards.

